An unbridled central bank governor?
Prague – Lately, the central banks of developed countries have been universally criticized.
The main points of criticism are as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their powers have expanded too quickly, and are now threatening the economy.
This notion – it's quite strange, as it's also popular among those who are supposed to be irreconcilably ideologically opposed, such as liberals and neo-Marxists – is utterly mistaken.
Critics failed to grasp that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation, but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Price levels are like human body temperature, they can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing severe symptoms.
In striking inflation caused by weak demand and curbing inflation driven by overly strong demand, central banks must be equally "active" as well.
Despite the battle being completely symmetrical, public assessment of this is mysteriously severely biased, especially in countries where people are very conservative with their finances.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. The Czech Republic's savers have a very small savings scale, and the loan-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czech people worry about inflation, even though Czech inflation rate reached its lowest level in 13 years last year, and since I took the position of vice governor of the Czech National Bank in 2013, the bank has been committed to eliminating the risk of deflation.
Another common criticism of developed countries' central bank policies since 2008 is that these policies have led to a redistributive effect.
So what if that's the case?
Any monetary policy action will redistribute wealth.
Raising interest rates delights savers, while lowering interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers like a strong currency; exporters like a weak currency.
To be effective, monetary policy must have different effects on different groups at different times.
This is not an error; this is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that, regardless of how hard central banks try, they have not achieved their inflation targets, so their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
At times, they even put these contradictory criticisms in one sentence, as if they are accusing someone of firing blanks but causing casualties.
In reality, central banks of developed countries have succeeded – and, I would say, quite remarkably so – in maintaining price stability and purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis.
Without their intervention, their economies would have faced a disastrous deflation, a sharp plunge in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, decisive action is the right approach to addressing a crisis (what role central banks played in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another issue).
In a system that employs a fiat currency with elasticity, to maintain roughly constant purchasing power, the money supply must change over time.
Therefore, long-term price stability, rather than the money supply, is the key issue.
The expansion of central banks' balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies since 2008.
In this context, central banks have taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and long-term price stability.
For them, there is no "activism" here; only an enduring mission to be fulfilled.
If you feel that this assertion has an air of arrogance to it, then let me provide some evidence.
The people vote with their wallets.
If their money's purchasing power was severely battered after 2008, they would naturally seek to exchange their currency (for other currencies, precious metals, or other forms of savings).
This is a rare occurrence in the developed world.
Of course, many central banks have failed to achieve their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define their ideal economic "temperature" as an inflation rate around 2% per annum.)
But this is certainly unpleasant, yet it will not lead to a disaster, particularly given that some of the price decline stems from supply-side shocks — rather than demand-side ones — such as the oil price plummeting to rock bottom.
This shock is beneficial to consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil importers.
Considering this scenario.
A company plans to increase sales by 2%, but its management can only achieve this in the form of a continuous 1% annual increase over two years.
Would you consider this company to be a failure?
You wouldn't consider that.
After all, private company plans and actual profits and revenues can easily deviate by 10% or more.
Most business operating variables for a large part of enterprises are below those of central banks.
Given the complexities of economic variables and the inherent inaccuracies in private company plans, how can you expect central banks to achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
I must clarify that I am not saying central banks should not strive to work towards their targets.
They absolutely should be doing so.
They should absolutely not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
However, when judging central banks, people need to keep things in perspective.
They indeed need to stop saying things that are not true — namely, that the central bank policy arsenal not only may be exhausted but has already been exhausted.
Monetary policymakers have an arsenal of weapons at their disposal and virtually unlimited ammunition to use at will.
These weapons have different calibers, and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economic bodies in all situations.
But central banks have theoretically unlimited ability to create and destroy money.
The central bank governor should tell people to stop making uninformed criticisms about them.
Our critics have not one of them been able to explain in a clear and credible way why price stability is a wrong target, what the central banks should be striving for as a key objective; and what drastically different measures they should have taken since 2008.
The reason is quite simple: the policies pursued by central banks in developed countries since the crisis have been the right ones.
In fact, this policy pulled our economy back from the brink.
You're welcome.
